If you initialize an object with a value, and then use the object initializer to set more properties, where one of those properties in some way is or encapsulates the value being initialized, the C# compiler reports an erroneous CS0165.

var state = new SomeObject()
{
    SomeProperty = new SomeOtherObject(state);
};

The aboves statement is actually just syntactic sugar for the following:

var state = new SomeObject();
state.SomeProperty = new SomeOtherObject(state);

Which is valid because at that point of assigning SomeProperty, state clearly has been initialized to something.

Interestingly, the refactoring tools recognize this and appropriate suggest the object initializer syntax, but as soon as you use it, the compiler complains.

